 has been<br />&gt; traditionally?<br /><br />Yes. Generally the rule should be that<br /><br />	make oldconfig<br /><br />with 'default values for all new options' should give you a configuration <br />that is essentially identical to the old one.<br /><br />So if it's a config option to enable compatibility with old kernels, it <br />should default to 'y'. If it's a new driver or a new feature that didn't <br />exist in previous kernels, it should default to 'n'.<br /><br />			Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
